At the end of the exchange, the Prague Stock Exchange fell into the negative
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Trades with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trades.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed with its fall of the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The market reaction to the outcome of the US House of Representatives vote, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilization plan, is thus perceptible here as well.
Fall of shares in Asia
The Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange’s Hang Seng Index lost four percent during trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange were losing more than five percent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“The hesitation about the U.S. bailout will affect financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk that other countries would be affected.
The bloodbath of American stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have devoted up to $700 billion (nearly K<0xC4><0x8D> 12 trillion).
The legislators thus deny the call for support for President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday and the main stock indices experienced the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones lost nearly seven percent, having seen a fall of this magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it emerged that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress Gives Up: U.S. Government Can Inject $700 Billion In Banks
The leaders of the U.S. Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial aid agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to the vote at the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a turning point in talks on adopting a bailout in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
However, success is not certain.
Indeed, before the final version of the law can be published and put to the vote, Congressmans must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be put to a vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout plan will be adopted is expected to be a first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market aid can be effective, a "disillusionment" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on what form the market stabilization package should take,” Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat, told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be carried out as early as Sunday.
On Saturday night, representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give the government a final form.
It should buy back unsold real estate assets from financial corporations that cause financial firms considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still have to pursue this market recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has had a significant impact on falling equity markets.
According to Democratic Sen. Harry Reid, lawmakers are making sure Congress reaches a final deal as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the congressional decision could affect trading on Monday.
At the moment, however, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will vote, or whether the negotiations will not be blocked at the last moment by this or that problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still be subject to many changes.
The total amount earmarked for aid to the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option of blocking the allocation of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of putting him in the minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are not able to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed with the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Sen. Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
Speaker Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of Golden Parachutes
Senate banking committee chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on accountability for the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the relief agreement, the unfolding of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for limiting such golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for property owners, who have problems paying for it.
The government should negotiate new installments for mortgages it will buy back, while reducing debtors' monthly payments and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological Aid
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization is going to be very difficult.
“And that’s because we don’t know what the mechanism and price of the problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on loss-sharing between the financial sector and the government," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not so important.
“It’s much more important that Congressmen agree this week to support this plan and that they will enshrine it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time," Marek stressed.
An extreme struggle: MP3 players against mobile phones.
We will advise you, how to choose
While almost all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are plenty of reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl records, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records on your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music on the move, i.e. compressed music, to put it simply - MP3 music.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand kroner for a reader, in the same way a Pink Floyd fan would struggle to bear headphones bought for twenty kroner at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also crucial.
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and SMS, it is able to play music and movies, record them, has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between reloads.
And music playback is one of the most important energy spurts.
Few mobile phones are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) are much better performers.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count on them to play music only for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second charger for work - this is true even for more expensive devices.
Problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of recharging, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the less performing.
Another problem arises when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, that a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do so without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As for the drives, you do not need, except for the exception (iPod), any software.
It is enough to fill, through the USB connector, the music device coming from the computer.
Most mobile phones and players will create a media library themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or according to the user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, similar to the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, pay particular attention to the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you are going to listen to it for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile that plays MP3.
Virtually all mobile phones are capable of this.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
Everyone can play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have precisely this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
All you have to do is visit the corresponding web pages of the operator (or of another provider) on your mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical mobile.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to fast-made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the internet, or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile on them.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which virtually all mobile phones have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an input for ordinary earphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
The readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Truly anyone can ensure the order of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (the M2 type, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand kroner.
But be careful.
The basic models support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive get away with it even with 8GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, a Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you must not spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile-walkmans instead (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of the control comes close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the farthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a longer battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the aforementioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
As a result of the European Commission's recent steps in regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), who has repeatedly stated that in Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, choired with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network does not seem to have much luck anymore (in fact, now it would be difficult to find frequencies).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable fall in prices, to which, subsequently, the conventional operators also had to react.
Yet even before troublemakers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to the ones we hear today were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
We should add that behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which among others owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
This is how in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain at least twice as cheap as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work also at home.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, at any rate, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not hidden, for a long time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
The future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
“At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of Telefonika O2's press department, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
“It is practically excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited time frame, we should have a concrete agreement now."
Instead, Vodafone is focusing on fulfilling requests for its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared fees and infrastructure.
This is what, in our opinion, means the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to discover a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in step with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
So what is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to get along like thieves in fairs. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, when the U:fon was created, was exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>’s web pages.
Nowadays, the U:fon lends itself as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová remarked on this: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not only the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in the Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached for the time being, as the offer from potential stakeholders has not been of sufficient interest to conventional operators," Kristián Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS External Relations Department said in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not come as a surprise on the part of representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an Office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: "Overseas, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile phone services."
However, putting pressure on the market to function honestly and to lower prices does not seem to be in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which flows from their reactions.
The question, whether this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all gas stations is probably due to the random and hard fight of the competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and consequently no operator has an increased corresponding responsibility for its behaviour in the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecoms regulator," Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Dropping responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in communications, whereby the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act did not include an expansion of the powers of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know this very well, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one's watching, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, but these are only partly public.
In most cases, it is about companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer customized mobile telephone services.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company made in front of the operator figure of a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special (and other) price offers.
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
“If what you are talking about happens, it could be a violation of the contractual terms that we would be looking at and that could result in a cessation of collaboration with the company in question,” Martina Kemrová replied to our question regarding this issue.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, has ruled against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible profits, and, at the same time, as opposed to the real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the same way as ordinary customers of mobile operators.
Now, this is precisely what should seem strange to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, another question arises at the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, the conventional operators made an effort, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries have intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they ended up getting the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies deal with this issue in the manner of a hot potato from which one gets rid by passing it on to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the beating.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at us, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS will only be able to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov m<0xC5><0xAF>j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Ji<0xC5><0x99>í B<0xC4><0x9B>lohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singing, a chorus and an instrumental version.
The song was performed by Kate<0xC5><0x99>ina Kn<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0xBE>ínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiá<0xC5><0xA1> and Jaroslav Kr<0xC4><0x8D>ek wrote the arrangements for the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
