Rats have feelings too.
A rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves the same way we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter difficult terrains because the Hardware does not fit.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it plays dead, runs away or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in steering and executing functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least, therefore, for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which is the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is different even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of Man: much of his existence being related to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, to be analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses great problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more readily accessible scientifically.
One could examine the processes of animal consciousness without taking into account their content, and this is exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach taken by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also underlines the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what does it mean for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as the reactions of the body) seizes on the living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely related to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluble nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to imput them to others other than ourselves.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities arise in the areas of the body sensation of the cortex and brainstem, just like Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could quite participate in transversal sensations of any kind.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is indisputable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in humans and rats is likely to be felt as fear in both cases: how could we check whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my view, similar behaviors are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Admittedly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain trunks, but cockroaches do not even have a brain.
But is the brainstem at the origin of the sensations?
And even if we could prove this for humans: how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations probably differ completely from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is nerve-wracking insofar as the same is true in rats and humans.
Since I do not explore the language and consciousness in rats, nor the sensations, I do not know if they exist.
This could be judged as short-term, but I’d rather move forward than constantly bump into a wall.
I am a pragmatic emotionalist.
