A Dark Street in the City, Often Forgotten, and May Soon Be on Sale.
New York has hundreds of avenues, boulevards, streets and other parallel roads, some famous, some only functional.
And even some veteran taxicabs and longtime local residents don't know how to get to Extra Place because they've never heard of it.
The street is in the East Village and runs north of First Street—not to be confused with Second Street—between Bowery and Second Avenue.
Approximately 30 feet wide by 120 feet long, it resembles a dusty driveway rather than an active artery.
. No signs indicate the street.
It is virtually impossible to find it on a standard atlas.
This street has admirers.
For example, there is Avalon Bay, the builder of the recent luxury buildings on First Street.
He would like to repave Extra Place, and create a smoother passage to the stores and boutiques, which should open in the new buildings.
Other admirers, including longtime neighbors, said they were charmed by this shortcut simply because it remains one of the last and oldest streets in the block.
But the Department of Preservation and Real Estate Development of the city that manages the street, has no interest in keeping it.
This month, at a meeting of neighborhood landlord committees, representatives from the city agency and Avalon Bay drafted a proposal allowing the builder to buy the street.
