"There are only a few spaces left that belong to the city, and we would like the city to keep Extra Place," she said.
"They could propose to rehabilitate it and manage it, which by the way Avalon could do, but we want to keep it public."
Avalon Bay announced several months ago that it wanted to replenish the small street and install seats, some of which would be used by a café to which the builder will grant space.
The proposal for this potential acquisition was made public at this month’s meeting.
Michele de Milly, the spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said that although the company wants to exploit the street, it does not necessarily mean that it wants to own it.
“Avalon Bay’s main interest is to relook this abandoned driveway, and make it public,” she said, noting that it was the city that suggested the sale.
Seth Donlin, a spokesperson for Real Estate Preservation, confirmed that the city wanted to sell the street, noting further that the agency's mission was to develop the property rather than manage it.
Compared to its more colorful neighbor, Bowery, Extra Place has left a slight historical imprint.
Some believe that Extra Place has been named after it since 1802, when the legacy of the large farm of Philip Minthorne's many children was divided, leaving aside this small piece of land, which has since remained abandoned.
The later entrance of the CBGB, a punk rock monument closed in 2006, reopened at Extra Place; the street is certainly more famous thanks to the cover photo of Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia"
