It was full of scrap, rags, barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.”
Some residents, including bloggers who had previously talked about the evolution toward luxury of the East Village, opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, saying that this humble little property should remain public.
Others have proclaimed Extra Place as a true rarity – a fragment virtually identical to the city that should be left in peace.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled "The Book of Contests: A Bitterly Nostalgic Look at a City in the Extinction Process") tells the story of the City and Extra Place, published in 1952 in The New Yorker.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow cul-de-sac, dark day and night, and bounded by the doors of a rusty iron warehouse and blinds, full of newspapers from last week that fly along the gutters."
With few exceptions, the street always looks the same.
