The Bilingual Debate: Immersion in the English Language
In this part of the Education Supervision program, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a former California student and former director of the education department at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Thought. Why Middle Classes Should Be Able to Choose Their School.”
Attracting the favors of Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are an interesting example of this.
Obama’s campaign emphasizes that “African and Latino students are less likely to graduate than white students.”
To combat these differences, Mr. Obama’s education program particularly supports, among many other topics, “bilingual transitional education” for those who learn English.
However, the question for Obama is whether his desire to pursue a bilingual education that advocates classroom instruction in languages other than English goes beyond his interest in eliminating differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The students at this school are mostly Hispanic, and low-income.
More than a third of the students, many of them newcomers, study English.
Among CM1 students, 100% have passed the 2008 State Math Examination, expert level.
Similarly, almost 93% of students have passed the English-Language-of-Arts exam
This incredible success was achieved thanks to another ingredient other than that advanced by Mr. Obama.
Sixth Street relies on analysis, practice, a constant assessment of capabilities and an exemplary attitude.
In addition, and this is an example that Mr. Obama could copy, reports Linda Mikels, head of Sixth Street, this school has introduced full immersion English language instruction.
Total immersion in the English language focuses on the almost constant use of English in instruction.
Ms. Mikels, opposed to bilingual education, told me "we had a huge success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, 12 months later, if you went without his class, you would have had no chance to identify him."
"It works," she observes, "it worked for us."
Shouldn’t Mr. Obama take the example of the Sixth Street Prep and replicate it in the other schools made up mostly of Hispanic students learning English.
The excellent results achieved by this school speak for themselves; but the policies on education within its party (the National Education Associations have long supported bilingual education) and its enormous support for bilingual education, obscure the prognosis of Mr. Obama’s response.
Although he favors the fact that immigrants learn English, Mr. Obama recently viewed this issue as insignificant, when he proclaimed that we must all stop polemizing about the wording of English-language laws.
“On the contrary,” he said, “you have to make sure your child speaks Spanish.”
If Mr. Obama really wants to eliminate differences, then he should carefully consider the models of education that work, rather than disdaining them or deeming them insignificant.
