Re-offenders of alcohol driving will have to install the 'alcocock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcohol, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents starting the vehicle in a state of drunkenness, or if he does not breathe.
The initiative was already announced last June and now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last a year.
Its goal is to reintegrate the driver by offering road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety, as well as the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Automotive Safety Foundation, will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for having driven more than once in a state of drunkenness, resume the car.
The alcoholock would prevent this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol content in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol content is higher than allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is at the expense of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced up to 65% of infringements during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, the reform done by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install this system in school buses as has been done in France.
