The Interview - Blood Becomes Safe Again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most importantly, he regained public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this tragedy and the grumbling of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from occurring again.
While Justice Krever was delaying the filing of his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee has fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its operations, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field in the years that followed, we regained the public's trust," she said, before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "confidence is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were seen in Europe, says the one that has held the strong since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the key recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of persons who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
Now, a few years ago, it has been demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle we applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors to be detected directly, rather than the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have made it possible to shorten the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors may be infected unknowingly and may not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be dispensed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the CEO of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
One never knows which pathogen will emerge in the system.
As recently as last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide a sufficient supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is getting older.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a refill of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which on average comprises only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network need to be renewed as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today’s life is so frantic, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand per year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
