Letters - A Dishonored Country
It was Mr. Vic Toews, former Justice Minister in the Harper cabinet, who last summer allowed himself to say of Louise Arbour that she was a "shame" for Canada.
To cast the reproach on this woman who has waged an unceasing struggle for justice and who deserves all our admiration says as much about the Prime Minister's entourage as it does about Stephen Harper himself.
This is a government that is the only one of all the Western countries involved that has not repatriated its national from the Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that does not take into account the fact that Omar Khadr was a very young teenager at the time of the charges against him.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, denies its word and lets a child soldier rot in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a parody of justice to assess the guilt of the accused.
As a reminder, UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, among others, are advocating for the repatriation of Omar Khadr so that he enjoys a fair trial in Canada.
