Shame, Mr. Toews, is there, in this resignation, and not elsewhere.
Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house without a penny in order to launch a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition as well as scare anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that she should have presented her view of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas and not with batons.
It was therefore enough for the mine to open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to distrust public opinion and rejects Black Canada's petitions and letters of support.
Perhaps Mr. Garver could explain how he can both call for a "public" debate while disregarding the views of that same public?
In the vice president's world, it seems that this word only refers to high-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a slap in the face (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice against the authors of Black Canada instructing them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, Barrick Gold’s pursuit is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that displease the wealthy businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate pursuit makes it clear that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for transparent debate.
It is a loss to academia, as it is to public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit such abusive prosecutions.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both houses of Congress.
It includes: better control by the elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of watch over the salaries paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday after a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards a deal that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Everything was done in such a way as to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” she said.
“This is the fundamental point: If we don’t do that, the trauma, chaos and disruption to Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned to sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would cause on the mood of investors.
The deadline we agreed on was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election were rather supportive of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that we are forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Sen. Barack Obama has added some provisions to the agreement, including allowing homeowners to keep their homes and the salary of executives of state-survived businesses.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he said on U.S. television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, responded: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The outlines that I’ve read [show] that it’s something we’re all going to have to digest and that we’re going to be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsaleable claims of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of debt securities (PCAAs) and resulting in a liquidity freeze and the debandade of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans who thwarted the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that we have emerged from this impasse since the Democrats accepted that some “toxic” assets of troubled companies are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the corners for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to incur losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first instalment of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain stakes in the rescued companies that will earn him dividends in case of profit and which he can resell when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to postpone seizure procedures for homes attached to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on compensation and severance payouts to the executives of the affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to the vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” House Finance Committee member Scott Garrett, a Republican, told his constituents.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
It is not about profiting the taxpayers.”
Speaker of a small group in Congress dubbed the “skeptic caucus,” Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully consider the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion (US$16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was renouncing to acquire its competitor in the middle of a shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s 20 largest banks and 10 largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In return, you get a vote in the bank and influence.
It’s precisely something that savers and households appreciate now that the times are looking uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed on track to nationalize another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all the loans underway at the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (US $ 75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander said yesterday that it would buy the branches and the customer accounts of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
His beauty in the eyes of azure was for a long time his card asset, some will say his weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, sensitivity and a talent that flowed from the source will also have removed him from the register of power that gives birth to the true sacred monsters.
What a great racer!
Paul Newman, who passed away Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer at his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema in his glory years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a sort of rival on screen, more cautious in his play, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breaking of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often makes beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a native Hungarian mother.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, the ultimate brand of quality.
For in him a whole country was projected in love with the self-made man, the fighter of the Pacific War, wounded in combat, who in the early 50s studied drama at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing in the theatre, on television, soon in the cinema.
The same man who campaigned for civil rights was also the car driver who finished second at the Le Mans 24 Hours in 1979, paired with a sex symbol, although a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
With him also disappear the shadows of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the splinters of show business, whose enigma we have not quite pierced.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The disappearance of Paul Newman made moviegoers dizzy this weekend, as his big roles on the black screen of memories collide.
More than half a century of an ever-changing seventh American art runs through it.
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on a Burning Roof adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all his promises.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role destined for James Dean, reprised after his death, which really released Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic villain in the brilliant The Sting (The Scam), Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen’s beautiful The Hustler (1961), he will reprise the character on the return in Martin Scorsese’s The Color of Money, which in 1987 earned him his only Oscar out of nine nominations.
That face through the ages, it was him.
It's him again.
Epochs are shaking through its course.
Young people know him best through George Roy Hill's cult Slap Shot (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Coen Brothers' The Hudsucker Proxy.
With a final role as a sponsor of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes’ Road to Perdition in 2003, the loop was closed.
Contrary to several film legends who gave up the profession early enough, Newman remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its golds, its splendours and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "as a living challenge to "underplaying" judging its performances too supported.
The profession has not always been tender for the handsome Paul Newman to whom the roles fell long baked in the beak.
However, he played less often the young first than the marginalized: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect traits reflected the drifts and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed unknown facets of his true modesty.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He lost his son Scott to an overdose and dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son to him, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rain of tributes that poured yesterday on Newman, his great boyfriend and former fellow-at-arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) stated, very saddened: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the deceased actor.
Beyond his legendary career, he is also a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the Hollywood drifts.
We will have seen much of his binette to sit on jars of dressing, sauces, cookies and other foods, judging the process of quite bad taste, although gag at first.
Nonetheless, the proceeds of these sales were donated to his Foundation for Children in Trouble.
Newman, rather than sit on his myth, will have committed himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these sentences: "Always and to the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was a privilege to be there.”
And it is a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a lucid and generous American artist.
Model citizen, in sum and in addition.
What could Zuschlag & Company do in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings concerning the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damage. Other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and use of forgeries.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand, into the pockets of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to collect money from subsidies obtained by issuing expense invoices, under which no real benefit was provided and thus the associations never fulfilled their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they procured notebooks at the Józsefváros market, while they manufactured the stamps at Kiskunhalas.
The names of companies that were to appear on the invoices were decided, inter alia, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the deposition of the latter, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they were going to introduce, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who, according to our information, was mainly responsible for drafting the files necessary for obtaining the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the Biztos Pont Egyesület association.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for as many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation, which would later bear the name of Együtt to Harmadik Evezredert, was teeming with errors of form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there, yet the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
The bill issuers with overflowing imagination also fell into excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounting, neither Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért nor Hoppá's name appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor's office.
Gy<0xC5><0x91>z<0xC5><0x91> Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecution summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were fake documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in the wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that, according to the invoice, a hundred people stayed there, did not fit, either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The zealous invoice issuers also did not inquire about the Budapest travel agencies of their choice, but only organized trips abroad, so they naively indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which is also contrary to the agency's accounting practices.
In addition, as it emerged during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up in the name of the Hotel Révfülöp to the order of Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, hotel employees only issue printed invoices, while the false ones were sent to the hand.
The prosecution's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes in mentioning the carriage of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not perform, since its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it is also for defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Evezredert Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and of Biztos Pont have been found to be false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó sports course, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Neither did the forgers pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at home, which is why, according to our information, the liquidator of the company denied issuing this invoice.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is that of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták Group, has issued an invoice to the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Evezredért for a sum of HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the manager of the company Collab Kft. was led to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Alapítvány Foundation, the association Atlasz Egyesület and the association Vörösfeny<0xC5><0x91> Egyesület.
There was no financial movement, either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this was avoided by the agencies from mentioning it in their accounts.
The following category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly related to the accused.
Thus, the administrative delegate of the general manager of the company Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade of fuel and motor vehicles, whose headquarters were in Budapest, but where he was not found, was Ivan Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Ivan Kubatov also reportedly sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
From what we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Evezredert Alapítvány, and that he pocketed their counter-value.
It was precisely at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In reality, none of these companies worked, which the accused explained by the fact that they were not receiving work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused as well as drafter of the founding documents of the companies, he established invoices in their names, in the order of associations related to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
Kubatov gave organizations a total of 15 invoices issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution believed that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices as well as VAT went into Kubatov’s pocket.
The man even used Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices that were used as part of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországárt applied for a grant to the socialist party's public benefit organization, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They received this grant in the amount of HUF 500,000 twice, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To prevent this from becoming known, five dummy invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, it was these invoices that were found during the search carried out in the office of <0xC3><0x81>rpád Kemecsei, at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the accused will report on the method of manufacturing the invoices, as they did before the Public Prosecutor's Office.
What could be really interesting would be that the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the slightest detail, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or perhaps the Socialists would have reached an agreement whereby in return for the reimbursement of a large part of the HUF 50 million, Zusi would wear the hat alone.
Today, the latter is probably offended, since the demands for his placement under house arrest, on the basis of a relief of his conditions of detention, continually fall into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of unreparable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait in their own homes for the end of the procedure. He does not have this possibility.
The Psychology of Overbidding: Why Are We Spending More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Researchers in neurology and economics at New York University have managed to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay a price that is too high.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group participated in a fun auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the surplus of a third, the whole under the brainstem, called striatum, was set in motion intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-stimulation" mechanism.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
In these, three groups overbid in front of a partner, in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they won the game, then they would receive an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received that $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis on one was on victory, while on the other, on failure.
By proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor in the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death.
There are an estimated 100 miles of patients in Hungary who carry the hepatitis virus, but only 7 miles are being treated because patients often don't know they are carrying the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases generated differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and organ fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers are advised to be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after the consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by a poor general condition, weakness, stomach ache and nausea.
Then a visible jaundice develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stools become lighter and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, one million people die each year from the most serious form of this disease, such as liver cancer or cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not known to have the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneakingly destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
There are currently 200 million people living with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does he who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing to what extent belief in God could influence human tolerance of pain.
As part of this bizarre experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Through a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments in which academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More precisely, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look sustainedly at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, focused on its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and in the meantime, received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed one.
The Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as “safe”, as someone who is “taken care of” and they “calmed down, and peace invaded them”.
At the sight of the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at the work of Leonardo.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided one finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image that they react to very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, an Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases, it actually changes our personality,” Wright added.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if we show the believers a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would the sight of a better quality Virgin Mary lead to better results?
You are what you disclose about yourself.
On the occasion of its tenth anniversary, Google claims that it can be found at the bottom of people's pockets as well as the sky above their heads. It knows where they spent their holidays, which specialists they consult and what their interests are.
Yet that is not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the influential people in society.
While skeptics draw a parallel with Orwell's horror vision, they don't see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary so that the founders of Google can meet their original goal that sounded like: “Let’s collect in one system all the information of the world!”.
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of global upheaval, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
Schmidt responded that he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "What can I do tomorrow?" or "What would work best for me?" However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, when it knows enough about users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during internet searches, the IP address of the computer that launches the search and the pages visited by the interested parties are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they have searched for, what they have clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will prefer to submit our products and services recorded on the basis of our previous statement.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my job is? ask users, who are worried about Google’s information monopoly.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can elicit fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can elicit a counter-reaction in Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the searched terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases, they are transmitted to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example in recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing an identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users were able to breathe a sigh of relief last May, when Google, upside down with the electronic legal protection body EFF, proved its rightfulness in court against the FBI. According to the judgment rendered, in the future, Google will still not be compelled by any of the points in the constitution to disclose information about the FBI’s secret request, of whatever nature
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms it had won over the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier, but ultimately failed to obtain lists of private users' searches, or the entire list of websites and keywords from the past two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their intimate sphere and their private domain suffer from it when they start to use Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is demonstrated against the multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its “savages” bringing together computer enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big business, the “connected corporation,” as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, cataloged as an invader of the world because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and program package, continuously refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, in the face of the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very exactly the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what the web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, draws precisely behind it.
Indeed, web 2.0 is nothing more than collaboration, the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the communication channels made available to us, and while the size of these changes one by one, the main thing remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link these to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then, he can link these to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also keep more photos than they automatically appear on F's stock blogs, in which they appear.
While we can get acquainted with many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands at the sight of the morning photos, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom his unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that fired one of his employees, just for the sincere opinions that this one has written on his blog about the top management, we can be sure of a private life:
One who lives an online life, is made up of what he shows of himself, and this is how we can define the principle behind the behavior of today's young people.
One wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to bypass Google’s monopoly, can do it (beginning, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but, at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them is not the least. Google online services, through text processing to image processing, to reading information can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked up to huge profiles of our servers and servers that do not have the best profiles.
The public expects, without really hiding from it, the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords/AdSense advertising domains threaten the revenue of advertising agencies, while the services introduced at an increasing speed cause serious migraines not only to Microsoft, but to many other computer companies.
However, the critical observers find, beside all this, contradictions having disturbing effects. For example, the top management of the company has refused, in its entirety, the protests of employees, after it has doubled the price of the corporate kindergarten and after the company has deemed too expensive the daily multiple catering, taken anytime after the company's google has already made it look derisive.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new medical services are not announced until they can be used. What is certain is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world on new points. While some think that the project of scanning and archiving Google's books and magazines takes on such important dimensions that the company's system will soon find itself in the hands of the court.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction authors. The novel by the famous Cory Doctorow, written with Orwellian halftones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way just through Google data.
