The smart car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What better way to develop barrier-avoiding technologies than by imitating an existing obstacle detector in nature?
For example, that of bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, buzzing bees gave the initial strategic idea to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how they should design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired, self-robot-controlled system, of the BR23C type, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee forms its own space, of oval shape, which in reality, looks a lot like our safe shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a primary role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance maneuver immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by an angle sufficient to avoid the collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If it were not so, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," says Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that the bees have to avoid the other bees, in our case, we have been able to use only the rotary movement, the acceleration as well as the slowing as maneuvers at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy concentration, making their lifespan longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory with a capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance. According to Nissan estimates, this system will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his way.
