In addition, the program differs from the original proposal made by the Bush administration, which mentioned that the $700 billion had to be spent in one go, to buy back the securities on dubious credits.
From now on, no more than half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after the law is passed by Congress, probably Monday. This first amount will be used by the Treasury Secretary to buy doubtful claims from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
Spending the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase dubious receivables, securities relating to dubious mortgages and mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" receivables.
Competent departmental officials have stated that buybacks can take place as part of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives companies the opportunity to participate in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that give rise to the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the necessary tools to provide $700 billion for the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast redemption of doubtful claims, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system leading to the collapse of one or the other major financial institution.
