On the other hand, bank leaders who are in a bad position and waiting for state aid can expect their severance pay, simply called a golden parachute across the Atlantic, to be capped by the government.
The salary cap is only mentioned in specific cases, and the limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers assistance to the company.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back as part of an auction, they will levy a surplus tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the repurchase of the bad debts, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that the amount paid to executives is not exaggerated.
