This is the first time in U.S. history that legal caps will be in place on directors-general appointments, said the chairman of the House Financial Benefits Committee, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the state obtains a right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since they can even be a winner in the case as soon as the economy and with it the rescued banks fall on their feet.
