Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, reports the Hungarian Central Statistical Office.
Industrial export selling prices increased by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier they decreased by 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 percent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors were only slightly higher by 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with bags and belts manufacturing in the first place with a monthly increase of 4.6 percent, followed by footwear production with a monthly increase of 2.5 percent.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of chemicals and products (1.6 percent).
Deflation resulted in oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and appliances manufacturing (0.9 per cent), as well as a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase, between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which play a significant role in domestic industrial operations, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of the gas price increase implemented by the authorities since July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of the processing sectors, it was the prices of the petroleum processing sector that experienced the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases occurred in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 percent to 9.1 percent.
Across the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Electricity, gas, steam and water supply prices were 18.7 percent higher than in the previous year.
Among domestic trade groups and by sector assignment, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was seen in August by those sectors that initiated profit on investment.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials production sectors for further processing did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the sectors of energy production and materials for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent was measured.
Export sales prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
