"An overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have high school diplomas, and as a result of poor quality elementary education, only a small part has the opportunity to obtain a higher education diploma."
In addition, Járóka stressed that education as an elementary human right plays a key role in enforcing other fundamental rights.
Investing in the early education of Roma children means strengthening the economies of the member countries of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these reports in the widest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Roma.
Indeed, the earlier a Roma child starts school, the greater his or her chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market; through taxes paid from his or her income and consumption, he or she participates in the state budget.
"Because of their nationality of the European Union, Roma must be assured of their right to a quality education, and be protected from a low-quality and sectarian education," - underlined Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the European Union's objective-oriented collaboration and action is necessary for an immediate acceleration of the process of desegregation of schools, for which compliance with existing and under preparation anti-discrimination directives is of paramount importance.
"The vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children must be given the democratic opportunities to participate as full citizens in the future of Europe," Járóka said.
In the name of the European Year of Equal Opportunities for all, the objective of the Summit for Equal Opportunities in Europe, held every year since the summit in Berlin last year, is to provide a single platform to support the measures taken to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination at European and Member State level.
