Mp3 player pointed finger, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a statement issued in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
According to the report, “5-10% of those who listen to music at full volume using portable music devices for at least 5 years, for more than an hour a day per week, are at risk of permanent hearing loss.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” Kuneva said.
“According to the scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
In addition, we need to re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists confirm that there are good reasons to be concerned, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
This data can be effectively limited by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of noise exposure.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods are at risk of permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This affects 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
