Elites are in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the $700 billion bailout approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms it communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions as well as to the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to “the people of Washington” and to the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, precisely, which made itself felt in a despotic way with the vote of which I spoke to you at the beginning.
However, what has just been cited is only one example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake is foreshadowing or already letting go: not only in the United States, but in the whole West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena incubated for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign state, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, obviously, close relations with foreign countries, but that, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears globally economically but politically, it is almost only national.
Political internationalisation seems really out of the way or has little to say: the obvious proof is provided by the European Union which, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, fails to decide on a common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a credit affection: when you go through a difficult period, it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of inestimable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new emphasis of the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that the more recent economic developments tend to attribute to a factor quite linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, indeed, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with the little material things.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but that are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than who is not, that is, who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadows.
And besides, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of estrangement that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes increases even more, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more foreign to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership, feeds in an underground way, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "arrivals" or else, in the collective mood changes of the last few times, from the conservative rise in Austria to Bavaria to the American victory in the Great Rebellion.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, have more and more difficulty, which does not date from today, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and agitates potentially in a demeaned way.
In view of all this, to speak of a current “rebellion of the masses” on the agenda, seems frankly exaggerated.
But they say well, keep your eyes wide open, it is not without reason.
The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
That is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to hold a 100 kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular structure of carbon, called nanocarbon tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal, a perfect adherence.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, it "detaches easily from the wall," says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
WALK ON THE WALLS? –” this material could be used as a temporary adhesive,” adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe yes, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since nano carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, California researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibers like hair, which self-cleanses dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and consistent adhesion.
