Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student housing market is not in crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin have to bear - explains the head of the design office of Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities, the strong demand from students has distorted the market so much that a process of generalized increase has started for them.
In most cases, the lease offers also include a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, without limit of rent, sub-leases.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of taxation are needed to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it goes from 650 euros minimum (Black Strip area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euros for a single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
One can only save if one moves away in the peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed you need 300/400 euros, for a single, you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari, for a bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by non-community students, have a subsequent anomaly: the rent demanded from foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities elect the historic rooms.
Historic movie theaters close in favor of multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-showrooms, and the consuming death of mono-showrooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems inescapable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of the way and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of a jury of Cannes, and who told the story of our life.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia-Romagna is at the forefront with 82 mono theaters lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-screen cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian farming has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favor of merchants: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect the existing laws.
To support the sector, between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year would be needed.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono-room cinemas in the historic centers and on the outskirts.
Among the planned regulations, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna putting in place other measures.
It is obvious, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve sound and image quality, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New Cinema Paradiso" which I had already been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotions, I turn to the other side to not see the panels blackened by dust.
