When energy is born from the waves, now the big ones are launched.
This is an oversized deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colosses like Chevron have set their eyes, and now try to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmentalists and the new increase in oil are giving a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore swell operating systems.
This would be twice the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides.
Colossians on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in the north of Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it looked like a real revolutionary step.
Two years ago, more and more candidates among these companies dedicated to traditional energy are betting on marine energy.
“Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesperson for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is evaluating the possibilities of cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the US Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the US continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which run the way of energy from the sea, and the amounts invested to date, although their details are unknown, indicate increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, due to the fact that marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to create a major problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, one must use technologies with a superior environmental impact.
"And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the sludge to move up and down, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through submarine cables.
At the moment, we have four such systems in the design phase, pending a single federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a mall and parking lot using six submarine turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of the water during the tides, rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, deserves right now, the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable from wind, sun, or waves, and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
And it is precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others, look to the coast, invested $7.5 million in 2008 and forecast investments of up to $35 million in 2009.
